title: Appointments to Veterinary Surgeons Board of Hong Kong
content_text:
p>
	The Government announced today (September 4) the appointment of a new member 
	and the re-appointment of eight incumbent members to the Veterinary Surgeons 
	Board of Hong Kong (VSB) from September 15, 2015 until such time as the 
	newly constituted VSB with elected members is established. The new member, Mr Timothy Ng Sau-kin, is the Park Operations Director of 
	Ocean Park Hong Kong. He was formerly chairman of the Animal Welfare 
	Advisory Group responsible for advising the Government on animal welfare

Advisory Group responsible for advising the Government on animal welfare 
	matters. The Secretary for Food and Health, Dr Ko Wing-man, welcomed Mr Ng and those 
	re-appointed to the VSB. He said he looked forward to their contribution to 
	the work of the VSB in upholding the professional standards of veterinary 
	surgeons in Hong Kong. Dr Ko also thanked the out-going member, Dr Doris Au Wai-ting, for her 
	dedicated service and valuable contribution to the VSB in the past seven

dedicated service and valuable contribution to the VSB in the past seven 
	years. Enacted in 1997, the Veterinary Surgeons Registration Ordinance (Cap 529) 
	provides for the establishment of the VSB, which is responsible for the 
	regulation of the practice of veterinary surgery, the registration of 
	veterinary surgeons, and the disciplinary control of the professional 
	activities of registered veterinary surgeons in Hong Kong. The Ordinance has been amended by the Veterinary Surgeons Registration

(Amendment) Ordinance 2015, passed by the Legislative Council on March 18, 
	2015. Among other proposals, the membership of the VSB will increase from 10 
	persons to 19. Six of the seats are to be filled by registered veterinary 
	surgeons elected by members of the profession. The Government is now working 
	on subsidiary legislation governing the election of registered veterinary 
	surgeons to the VSB. Subject to passage of the proposed subsidiary 
	legislation through the Legislative Council, the election is expected to

legislation through the Legislative Council, the election is expected to take place in 2016. As and when the elected members are in place to join the VSB, the Government will bring the amendment ordinance into full operation. That future date is also expected to be the time at which the newly constituted VSB will come into being. Following is the membership list of the VSB as from September 15: Chairman
